{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625931"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:32:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:32:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17050"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17050"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74038"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9740"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59514"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5136"},{"type":"tags","id":"5137"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23069"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74038"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EStool softeners are commonly prescribed medications used to treat and prevent constipation, particularly in patients who should avoid straining during defaecation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of docusate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces surface tension and increases water and lipid penetration","Stimulates intestinal smooth muscle contraction","Increases intestinal fluid secretion","Provides bulk to stool through water absorption","Lubricates the intestinal wall"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing surface tension and increasing water and lipid penetration\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of docusate. As an anionic surfactant, it allows better water and lipid penetration into stool, resulting in softer stools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating intestinal smooth muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of stimulant laxatives such as bisacodyl.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing intestinal fluid secretion\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism by which osmotic laxatives such as magnesium citrate work.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding bulk to stool through water absorption\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of bulk-forming laxatives such as psyllium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELubricating the intestinal wall\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for mineral oil and other lubricant laxatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStool softeners are required in patients who need to avoid straining during defaecation, e.g. recent hernia surgery where increasing intraabdominal pressure must be avoided or those with cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Docusate is an anionic surfactant that reduces the surface tension of stool and increases water penetration.","Stool softeners work by allowing water and fats to mix more easily with solid stool matter.","Stool softeners are not stimulant laxatives and do not directly increase bowel motility."],"references":[]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59514"}},"question":{"data